\omega_{\mathrm{p} 2} \cong \frac{\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{gd} 1}}{\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{gs} 1}+\mathrm{C}_{\mathrm{gd} 1}} \frac{\mathrm{~g}_{\mathrm{m} 1}}{\mathrm{C}_{2}} \tag{4.133}
\end{gather*}
$$

Note that both $\omega_{\mathrm{p} 2}$ and $\omega_{\mathrm{z}}$ are proportional to the transistor's transconductance $\mathrm{g}_{\mathrm{m} 1}$; a large transconductance is vital for minimizing the adverse effects of the second pole and the zero by shifting them to higher frequencies.

