\frac{C_{1} C_{2}}{C_{1}+C_{2}}=\frac{(1+A) C \cdot\left(1+\frac{1}{A}\right) C}{(1+A) C+\left(1+\frac{1}{A}\right) C}=\frac{\left(A+2+\frac{1}{A}\right) C^{2}}{\left(A+2+\frac{1}{A}\right) C}=C
$$

When C is split into C1 and C2 as shown in Fig. 4.16, a new (fictitious) node is created at $V_{x}$, whose potential is a simple voltage division between $\mathrm{V}_{1}$ and $\mathrm{V}_{2}$.

$$
\begin{equation*}
