The strength of the Miller theorem lies in its ability to greatly simplify the analysis for the dominant pole of a circuit with a capacitor between the input and output of an inverting high-gain amplifier, as we will see. However, the Miller theorem is not applicable when estimating the second pole of amplifiers. At frequencies where capacitive loading at node $\mathrm{V}_{2}$, responsible for the second pole, becomes significant, the gain between nodes $\mathrm{V}_{1}$ and $\mathrm{V}_{2}$ begins to decline. Therefore, $|A(\omega)|$ can no longer be assumed constant, making the application of the Miller theorem challenging.

